# Web-tooling Workload Introduction

Web-tooling benchmark is a public benchmark which is designed to measure the JavaScript-related workloads commonly used by web developers, such as the core workloads in popular tools like Babel or TypeScript.

This workload is developed by Intel to make the deployment and measurement on multi-core servers more conveniently. It runs the test as long as users specify the benchmark docker image and instances number.

It supports below features by default:
- Containerization deployment, default OS is Ubuntu 22.04 LTS and Node.js is Node 18.12.0 LTS
- Run single workload instance
- Run multiple workloads instances
- Start multiple workloads at the same time to make true parallel
- Provide web-tooling raw data and congregated result

After some simple tweaks, it can support:
- Run other workloads like Ghost.js, FaaS startup etc.
- Run different node versions

## (Optional) Proxy Setup

Ensure that you have variables `http_proxy` and `https_proxy` set in your
terminal. E.g.
   ```bash
   http_proxy=http://proxy.ali.com:1000/
   https_proxy=http://proxy.ali.com:1000/
   ```

## Building the workload

```bash
docker build -t webtooling-baseline .
```
where `webtooling-baseline` can be changed by users.

## Running the workload

```bash
./webtooling.sh webtooling-baseline 1
```

where `webtooling-baseline` is the workload docker image name in previous building step. `1` is the workload instances start in parallel. To the many core server fully utilized users may want to specify instance number to vCPU number. E.g, for Icelake 2-socket 32C platform, the vCPU number is 128.

## Check results

After running the script a `results` folder will be generated at upper level folder. Inside that
folder a `json` file with all the Web tooling benchmark results for each of the containers will be generated.

Below is a sample json file for 128 instances running.
